definition.value: A medium-chain fatty acid that is lauric acid substituted at position 11 by a hydroxy group.

label.value: EC 3.6.4.* (hydrolases acting on ATP; involved in cellular and subcellular movement) inhibitor

definition.value: An EC 3.6.* (hydrolases acting on acid anhydrides) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any such enzyme acting on ATP and involved in cellular and subcellular movement (EC 3.6.4.*).
An EC 3.6.4.* (hydrolases acting on ATP; involved in cellular and subcellular movement) inhibitor that interferes with the action of a non-chaperonin molecular chaperone ATPase (EC 3.6.4.10).
An EC 3.4.21.* (serine endopeptidase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of trypsin (EC 3.4.21.4).

A generic class of anionic phospholipids, encompassing phosphorylated derivatives of sphinganine, its homologues and stereoisomers, as well as the hydroxy and unsaturated derivatives of these compounds.
A tetracarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the four carboxy groups of beta-citrylglutamic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at positions 8(17) and 13 (the latter with E-stereochemistry) and carries a hydroxy group at the terminal C-15 position.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at positions 8(17) and 14 and carries an S-hydroxy group at position 13.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at positions 8(17) and 14 and carries an R-hydroxy group at position 13.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in fungi, the kingdom that includes microorganisms such as the yeasts and moulds.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at positions 8(17) and 14 and carries an S-hydroxy group at position 13.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at positions 8(17) and 13 (the latter with E-stereochemistry) and carries a hydroxy group at the terminal C-15 position.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at positions 8(17) and 13 (the latter with E-stereochemistry) and carries a hydroxy group at the terminal C-15 position.
A 17(18)-EpETE in which the epoxy group has (17R,18S)-configuration.
A labdane diterpenoid in which the labdane skeleton has double bonds at positions 8(17) and 14 and carries an S-hydroxy group at position 13.
A 17(18)-EpETE in which the epoxy group has (17S,18R)-configuration.
Any fungal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in the mould, Aspergillus.
An acylsphingosine in which the acyl moiety contains 24 carbons and 1 double bond with a hydroxy group at position 2.
A HEPE obtained by hydroxylation at position 19 of all-cis-5,8,11,14,17-icosapentaenoic acid.
Any fungal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in the mould, Chaetomium.
A HEPE obtained by hydroxylation at position 20 of all-cis-5,8,11,14,17-icosapentaenoic acid.
Any fungal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Penicillium.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid that is arachidonic acid substituted at position 20 by an oxo group.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-icosatetraene in which the two methyl groups are replaced by carboxy groups.
Any human metabolite produced by metabolism of a xenobiotic compound in humans.
Any fungal  metabolite produced by metabolism of a xenobiotic compound in fungi.
Any prokaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in bacteria.
Any bacterial metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Escherichia coli.
Any bacterial metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Streptococcus pneumoniae.
Any bacterial metabolite produced by metabolism of a xenobiotic compound in bacteria.
A hormone antagonist that blocks corticotropin-releasing factor receptors
A triglyceride obtained by acylation of the three hydroxy groups of glycerol by octanoic acid. Used as an alternative energy source to glucose for patients with mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease.
1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which both the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as octanoyl. Formula C19H36O5.
A long-chain fatty acid that is behenic (docosanoic) acid substituted at position 2 by a hydroxy group.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 3-[(1-carboxyvinyl)oxy]benzoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which both the 2- and 3-acyl groups are specified as octanoyl.

A urea in which one of the hydrogens attached to a nitrogen of the urea group is replaced by a sulfonyl group. The N-sulfonylurea moiety is a key group in various herbicides, as well as in a number of antidiabetic drugs used in the management of type 2 diabetis mellitus.
A very long-chain fatty acid that is hexacosanoic (cerotic) acid substituted at position 2 by a hydroxy group.

A derivative of phenol which has an acetamido substituent located meta to the phenolic -OH group. It is a non-toxic regioisomer of paracetamol with analgesic properties, but has never been marketed as a drug.
A synthetic or semi-synthetic compound that has oestrogenic activity.
Any compound produced by a plant that happens to have estrogenic activity.
Any compound produced by a fungus that happens to have estrogenic activity.
A D-galactosyl-N-acylsphingosine where the ceramide N-acyl group is nervonoyl [(15Z)-tetracos-15-enoyl] and the D-galactosyl component has beta anomeric configuration.
A long-chain fatty acid that is arachidic (icosanoic) acid substituted at position 2 by a hydroxy group.
Any 3-hydroxyacyl group in which the carbon bearing the hydroxy substituent has R configuration.
Any univalent carboacyl group that is derived from a 3-oxocarboxylic acid.
An extended flavonoid resulting from the formal fusion of a benzene ring with the h side of flavone. A synthetic compound, it is an inhibitor of aromatase (EC 1.14.14.14).
A (3R)-3-hydroxyacyl group derived from (3R)-3-hydroxydecanoic acid.
A trans-2-enoyl group derived from trans-dec-2-enoic acid.
An antagonist that binds to and activates aryl hydrocarbon receptors (AhRs).
